    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-13T11:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-13T11:29:00-05:00" n="310"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/217</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d310fn3">Sent via the Legation in Sweden (No. 908, Nov.
                        15).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Petrograd</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-13T20:00:00+03:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 13, 1917, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received November 17, 6.10 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1979. Tell <persName corresp="#p_WD1">Willard</persName> learned that <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> left Moscow yesterday in car 466 for
                    Vologda where car will be connected with Siberian express leaving Petrograd
                    to-night. <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> accompanied by Russian
                    railroad official, son and interpreter. High railroad official who accompanied
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> from Petrograd gave this
                    information to the <pb facs="0258" n="208" xml:id="pg_208"/> Department of Ways
                    of Communication to-day from Moscow and said he returned to Petrograd and that
                    above disposition of car made on <persName corresp="#p_SJF1"
                    >Stevens</persName>’s urgent request and furthermore that he had delivered to
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> in Moscow my telegram copy of
                    which cabled you in my 1973. Have nothing from <persName corresp="#p_SJF1"
                        >Stevens</persName> direct. Considerable fighting reported in Moscow
                    streets. Suggest you cable <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName>, care
                    of American Consul, Harbin, to await instructions there. Suppose you informed
                    concerning conditions here by my cables to the Department. Some government will
                    be established here when <persName corresp="#p_ECH1">Emerson</persName> arrives
                    Vladivostok and although I may possibly not advise recognition thereof think any
                    ministry will be pleased to utilize <persName corresp="#p_SJF1"
                        >Stevens</persName>’s and <persName corresp="#p_ECH1">Emerson</persName>’s
                    force. Moreover tender of their services may be necessary to justify us [in]
                    charging Russia with expense incurred which was undoubtedly stipulated to be
                    paid from advances made Russia. Please answer. …</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
